  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't something I've ever really encountered myself, but I've seen it play out in the lives of my kids and neighbors. My daughter, who's in high school, often talks about how she feels like she's not smart enough in math class because her teachers and classmates assume she's not going to do well. That's stereotype threat at work—when people internalize negative stereotypes about their group and it affects their performance. I've also heard stories from my ex-wife's friends, who are women in engineering, saying they get nervous during exams because they worry they'll confirm the stereotype that women aren't good at math. It's a real problem that needs to be addressed, but the way we do it matters. We can't just say 'be confident' and expect it to fix everything. What we need is real support—like mentorship programs that pair students with someone who's been through the same struggles, or schools that teach students to recognize and challenge stereotypes early on. But the biggest issue is that stereotype threat isn't just about individual confidence; it's about systemic issues in how we teach and evaluate people. For example, in my city, many schools still use standardized tests that don't reflect the diversity of learning styles, which can make some students feel like they're failing because of the test, not because they don't know the material. We need to address the root causes, not just the symptoms. It's hard to do this when you're depressed and struggling with your own mental health, but it's important to try. Maybe we should start by listening to the people who are most affected—like the students themselves—and give them the tools they need to succeed.",
